      "depositedDate": "2025-09-23T03:03:53+01:00",
      "abstract": "NPS NRP Executive SummaryZero Trust Architecture (ZTA) security was adopted by the DOD (Freter, 2022; DISA, 2022), pursuant to the Presidential Executive Order on 12 May 2021 (Biden, 2021). The framework and implementation of ZTA by the DOD is currently at an early stage of development for many use cases. This research project evaluates zero trust (ZT) implementation from three separate perspectives: • Navy shipboard ZT, as it relates to the Consolidated Afloat Network Enterprise System (CANES), focusing on user continuous authentication (CA) (Dodd, 2023). • U.S. Marine Corp ground units at the tactical edge (ATE), addressing key architectural features to address ZT requirements (Oshiro, 2023). • Joint coalition forces ZT at the tactical level; ongoing thesis research by Thomas Schmitt, completion estimated September 2024. The key finding for Navy adoption of ZT for CANES is that the initial best course of action is to assess what current software and hardware systems would work best in situ before implementing full ZTA. A micro-segmentation next generation firewall was assessed along with CA software. A suitable candidate software, TypingDNA ActiveLock (TypingDNA, n.d.), was determined based on Navy afloat needs, which, in a preliminary assessment, was found to work well for CA. The key finding for the USMC ATE research, after investigating and assessing the security requirements using Spoofing, Tampering, Repudiation, Information disclosure, Denial of service, Elevation of privilege (STRIDE) (Meier et al., 2003) and tactical edge mission requirements, was a base framework that can be used for Tactical Zero Trust Architecture (TZTA). This framework was assessed against various tactical edge mission types, and other necessary framework parts were determined to be added to the base framework. The final study focusing on ZTA in sharing of information with coalition partners is not yet completed.Approved for public release. Distribution is unlimited.This research is supported by funding from the Naval Postgraduate School, Naval Research Program (PE0605853N/2098). https://nps.edu/nrpChief of Naval Operations (CNO)N2/N6 - Information Warfar",
